On Wednesday on 18th of May, the Czech government approved amendments to the terms of humanitarian assistance payment to Ukrainian refugees.
Today, all arriving Ukrainian refugees are entitled to a first assistance payment of 5,000 crowns without any additional conditions (only a Temporary Protection visa is needed).
To receive the same amount in the subsequent five months, the applicant must prove his/her difficult financial situation ‚Äì an unemployed status, the absence of property in the Czech Republic etc.
Ministry of Labor decided to change that practice as follows:
1Ô∏è‚É£ Assistance first payment will no longer be unconditional.
If the refugee has been provided with free accommodation, daily multiple meals and hygiene supplies, he/she won't be able to claim a payment of 5,000 crowns.
Authorities will consider that basic assistance has been provided in-kind (accommodation, meals and hygiene supplies) and therefore the purpose of humanitarian assistance has been fulfilled and there is no need for paying money.
This measure is intended to solve a problem with the gypsy refugees from Ukraine.
Many of them come to the Czech Republic only for financial assistance.
2Ô∏è‚É£ entitlement to a payment of second, third, fourth, fifth and sixth assistance will still have only those refugees, who prove direct need (unemployment etc.).
However, two more conditions will be added:
üìå as stated in the first paragraph, cash assistance be able to get only those Ukrainians, who hasn't been provided with free accommodation, daily multiple meals and hygiene supplies;
üìå the applicant must physically reside in the Czech Republic.
This is necessary to stop the practice "tourism for sake of assistance", when the refugee lives in one country and come to the Czech Republic for a few days solely for the money.
According to the law, every alien should inform MIA of the change of residence within three working days after moving.
If the address on the questionnaire for assistance payment doesn't match the address indicated in MIA database, the applicant will be asked to provide evidence on the fact of living in the Czech Republic.
Otherwise, the assistance payment will be denied.
Currently, the Czech Republic has spent 2,626 billion crowns on humanitarian assistance payment.
