How does Poland provide assistance to Ukrainians
The Czech Republic has hosted up to half a million Ukrainians, which has had a significant impact on the Czechs' daily life.
There are long queues at labor offices, and significant price increases are being observed in shops.
What is currently happening in Poland, which has hosted millions of Ukrainian refugees?
When hostilities broke out, the Polish government quickly organized and commenced providing assistance.
It was anticipated.
In recent months, there have been discussions in Poland about the emergence of such a significant issue.
Even in Ukraine, there was much less preparation for what was going to happen, while Poland was actively preparing.
For instance, there were already plans in place regarding the placement of refugees from Ukraine in the border regions of Poland and Ukraine, even prior to the onset of the war.
In Ukraine, there hasn't even been a consideration that such a thing could happen.
I have heard that there was mockery regarding Poland's fear of the refugees.
However, it was a well-considered decision to prepare for all of these events before the onset of the war.
I would like to emphasize that a substantial amount of funding was allocated from regional and state budgets to assist Ukrainians fleeing from the bombing by the Russian aggressor.
First and foremost, assistance was provided in logistics, specifically in facilitating movement throughout the territory of Poland.
There are special trains from Ukraine to Poland, including medical trains for the wounded and sick.
There are airplanes flying through the territory of Poland, connecting cities within the country, as well as charter flights to EU countries.
I have had the experience of collaborating with flights to Portugal, France, Romania, and Spain from Lublin.
Although Lublin is comparable in size to Lutsk, it does not have a population exceeding one million, as one might assume.
The transportation issue remains of great importance.
The passenger fare for Ukrainians has been waived in Poland.
They can travel on trains and public transport free of charge.
Furthermore, Poland has reached an agreement with German carriers who have organized free trains from several Polish cities to Germany.
This means that refugees have the opportunity to reach their intended destinations free of charge.
Another important aspect is the accommodation of refugees in facilities provided by local self-government authorities.
Typically, these consist of small enclosed school stadiums or complexes where temporary halls are equipped with beds.
Additionally, free meals and medical first aid are provided at these facilities.
Refugees have the opportunity to rest and stay for several days, while on-site efforts are made to explore possibilities for relocating them to more comfortable conditions.
Cities like Warsaw, Gdansk, and Wroclaw have recently intensified their activities, leading to the establishment of entire Ukrainian neighborhoods in these areas.
The case of Warsaw is unique in that they were able to negotiate with the Russian Embassy to reclaim the facilities that were vacated by the embassy staff.
For decades, large residential complexes remained abandoned, with Russians not granting access to anyone.
The Polish local authorities effectively nationalized these complexes.
They took them over for the benefit of Ukrainians, and now Ukrainian families will reside there.
These are multi-family housing units that can accommodate 200‚Äì300 families at once.
The buildings will be provided with water and electricity, and they have been insulated.
Refugees from Ukraine will be able to begin living there within a week or two.
The third aspect is social care.
After February 24th, Poland took a unique step: the Sejm passed a law on refugees from Ukraine, which was later approved by the Senate.
According to this law, Ukrainian citizens are granted the right to legally stay in Poland for a period of 18 months.
They have the right to work without a work permit, which is mandatory in all European countries.
This law includes provisions for medical services.
In addition, there is a private fund that has allocated ten million zlotych for providing free medication assistance to Ukrainians.
You simply need to send an SMS message and receive a code on your phone.
And you can receive medications in Poland for free, up to the equivalent amount of 5,000 hryvnias.
Social care includes an amount of three hundred zlotych, which is given to every refugee from Ukraine, regardless of age, and is provided without the need for repayment.
Various funds, such as Caritas and the Red Cross, are widely available, providing packages containing food, household items, and clothing.
